What a cool and outstanding feature in AZURE networking.
We can keep our resources in hub and spoke model, exactly what you are imagining in your head.
In enterprise architecture, it is on the basis of Multiple subscriptions where 1 become hub and others become spoke.
The main idea behind hub is to hold the shared and crucial infa within it. Like firewall/Expressgateway/DC
while this is not feasible for me in my lab, i went by 1 subscription and multiple resource groups within it.
keeping 1 RD as Hub and all others as Spoke.
keep in mind as always do not try to keep VNETS from same address space, otherwise Azure will not let you peer them
Reason is simple what if in future you create a subnet from those VNETS which are overlapping, how will azure decide destination.
So, keep completely different VNETS for all RG like (10.1.0.0/16,10.2.0.0/16,10.3.0.0/16,10.4.0.0/16) Keeping your vnets like this gives 
enough room for scaling by configuring multiple subnets within 1 VNET.
LEARNING 1 - 
What exactly defines HUB & SPOKE - 
when our spokes can communicate with hub on required ports or services but not directly between spokes.
To enable talk between HUB & SPOKE - we just need to enable peering.
We must not enable peering between spokes as that will defy our purpose of segmentation.
Also, the sole purpose of keeping hub in picture was to ensure that all traffic goes via HUB only.
